</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[138,233,1453,1477]" box="[138,233,1453,1477]" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041">
<emphasis box="[138,233,1453,1477]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[138,1185,1502,1685]" lastBlockId="13.[125,1172,137,193]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="4042" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041">
In having a wholly yellow mesonotum and, especially, a peculiar structure of the male terminalia, 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2006" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2006" box="[271,422,1533,1557]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phomyaaw" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[271,422,1533,1557]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041">P. phomyaaw</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[430,522,1533,1557]" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2006" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2006" box="[824,974,1533,1557]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gaemluang" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[824,974,1533,1557]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041">P. gaemluang</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[982,1074,1533,1557]" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
It can be readily distinguished from the latter by partly brownish thoracic pleura and by two and four very long bristles on abdominal sternites 5 and 6, respectively. Two other species with wholly yellow mesonotum are 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bezzi" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[493,646,1629,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="candidiseta">
<emphasis box="[493,646,1629,1653]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041">P. candidiseta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[706,897,1629,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanguinolentus">
<emphasis box="[706,897,1629,1653]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041">P. sanguinolentus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bezzi M" box="[913,1048,1629,1653]" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" pagination="442 - 496" refId="ref15141" refString="Bezzi M. 1912. Rhagionidae et Empididae ex insula Formosa a clar. H. Sauter missae. Annales Historico- Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici 10: 442 - 496." type="journal article" year="1912">Bezzi 1912</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="de Meijere JCH" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" pagination="1 - 99" refId="ref15320" refString="de Meijere JCH. 1914. Studien uber Sudostasiatische Dipteren. VIII. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 56: 1 - 99." type="journal article" year="1914">de Meijere 1914</bibRefCitation>
). The former differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2006" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2006" box="[506,656,1661,1685]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phomyaaw" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[506,656,1661,1685]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041">P. phomyaaw</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[664,755,1661,1685]" pageId="12" pageNumber="4041" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by wholly black thoracic pleura. The latter can be readily distinguished from the new species by the wholly black scutellum and largely black thoracic pleura.
</paragraph>
